## Exchange 1: Cyber Range Team Initial Response

**From:** Cyber Range Team
**To:** Aya (on behalf of Netstrike)
**Subject:** Project direction and suggested idea

### Summary

The Cyber Range team responded to the team's initial outreach with two items: suggested
reading to ground the team's understanding of cyber ranges as a concept, and a proposed
project idea for the team to consider.

### Suggested Reading

Two papers were recommended before proceeding with any design decisions:

- *A Systematic Review of Cyber Range Taxonomies: Trends, Gaps, and a Proposed
  Taxonomy*: MDPI Future Internet, 2025.
  https://www.mdpi.com/1999-5903/17/6/259
- *A Step-by-Step Definition of a Reference Architecture for Cyber Ranges*:
  ScienceDirect, 2024.
  https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2214212624002199

### Cyber Range Team's Current Project (CRANE)

The Cyber Range team clarified the scope of their own development work:

- Current cyber range implementations suffer from limited interoperability and
  portability due to reliance on specific virtualization infrastructures.
- Their project (referred to as CRANE going forward) aims to build an open-source
  cyber range using **Packer, Terraform, and Ansible** (Infrastructure as Code).
- The goal is to enable scenario deployment on any virtualization infrastructure
  (Proxmox, OpenNebula, Incus) using the same asset and scenario definitions.

### Proposed Idea for Netstrike

The Cyber Range team proposed that the capstone team build an **NPM library for
visual scenario construction**, based on Vue.js and Vue Flow. Requirements outlined:

- Allow users to build scenarios visually (drag-and-drop interface)
- Provide interfaces for defining assets, nodes, and networks
- Validate whether a network design is structurally valid
- Translate the visual representation into formats supported by existing cyber range
  implementations

The team noted this idea would be reusable by any Vue.js project as an npm library.

### Caveat from Cyber Range Team

The Cyber Range team explicitly noted that the visual builder idea **may not allow deep
exploration of the cybersecurity field**, and encouraged the team to consider
cybersecurity-focused alternatives: for example, developing a scenario or a
cybersecurity tool usable within the cyber range. They asked the team not to rush a
decision and to discuss with teammates and supervisor first.

